The diseases of globalisation
Globalisation is put to the toughest test as never before.
Tensions are simmering everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnant or struggling with an economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are stuck in slow growth and risk a new recession.
The war is now threatening in Iraq.
For advocates of open markets and free exchange, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalisation so threatened?
Why are its advantages apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalisation be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely enough.
Certain regions of the world have withdrawn large benefits from globalisation, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Certain regions, however, have withdrawn meager benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The US government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, claim American leaders, is caused by the inability of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let's consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades while a large number of Asian countries that were among the worst in international comparisons of government (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
The countries with high population and therefore the large domestic markets tend to grow more quickly than the countries with low population.
(As all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
The coastal countries tend to be more performing than the landlocked countries.
The countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than the countries with lower levels of malaria.
The developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performing than the countries that are far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If the rich countries do not care about these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to grow.
If rich countries blame unfortunate countries for claiming they are somehow culturally or politically unable to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify disturbances.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move to a more serious approach to globalization than what is offered by the rich countries, and particularly the United States.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely, to answer the basic needs of the poorest people in the world.
In some cases, their sufferings can be alleviated mainly thanks to better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distances from markets, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing rich countries giving more lectures on poor countries' bad governance, real solutions require rich countries to offer sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most ingrained barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation in a striking way.
The control of diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing survival medicines and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least around 40 dollars per person per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than 2,000 dollars per person per year on healthcare, but it exceeds the reach of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of 200 dollars per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire annual income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers due to diseases as long as it does not receive adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins", we should offer careful diagnoses, like any good doctor would, for each country and each region, to understand the fundamental factors that delay their economic growth and development.
In regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the main problem is mainly caused by geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
The rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Black Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, fertile soils, and educational opportunities development.
Foreign aid is once again required.
In other regions, the main problems concern the lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take seriously the complexities inherent to globalization.
The Washington consensus ideology of one size fits all is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of making globalization benefit everyone.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
